1. What is Iterable?
👉 Iterable is the root interface of the Java Collections Framework that allows objects to be traversed (iterated)
one by one.
2. Package & Syntax:
Package: java.lang
Declaration:
public interface Iterable<T>
👉 It uses generics (<T>) → works with any data type

3. Position in Hierarchy
Iterable (Top)
   ↓
Collection
   ↓
List / Set / Queue

👉 All collections like ArrayList, HashSet, LinkedList implement Iterable

4. Methods in Iterable
🔹 Main Method
Iterator<T> iterator();
👉 Returns an Iterator to traverse elements

Default Methods (Java 8+)
1. forEach()
default void forEach(Consumer<? super T> action)
👉 Applies action to each element
list.forEach(n -> System.out.println(n));
2. spliterator()
default Spliterator<T> spliterator();
👉 Used for parallel processing (advanced)

Steps:
Call iterator()
Use hasNext() → check next element
Use next() → get element

Using for-each loop
List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(10);
list.add(20);

for (int num : list) {
    System.out.println(num);
}

👉 Works because List implements Iterable

Using Iterator explicitly
Iterator<Integer> it = list.iterator();

while (it.hasNext()) {
    System.out.println(it.next());
}

| Feature | Iterable         | Iterator              |
| ------- | ---------------- | --------------------- |
| Type    | Interface        | Interface             |
| Purpose | Provide iterator | Traverse elements     |
| Method  | `iterator()`     | `hasNext()`, `next()` |
| Usage   | for-each loop    | Manual traversal      |

8. Why Iterable is Important
Enables for-each loop 
Provides standard way to traverse collections 
Reduces complexity (no index needed) 
Works with all major collections 

9. Limitations
Cannot move backwards ❌
Cannot access index ❌
Only forward traversal ❌

11. Key Points to Remember
Root interface of collections
Present in java.lang
Uses generics
Only one abstract method → iterator()
Enables for-each loop
Works with Iterator internally











